## Moving Content Between Parts

### When to Move Theory → Experiments:

**Indicators:**
- Section title: "Experiment:", "Implementation:", "Results:", "Validation:"
- Contains phrases: "We implemented...", "We trained...", "We measured..."
- Shows plots of actual data
- Describes computational procedures
- Reports timing/memory measurements

**Example Migration:**
```latex
% WRONG: In theory chapter
\section{Validation of Heliomorphic Completeness}
We implemented the heliomorphic function using PyTorch and trained
it on MNIST. The results show...

% RIGHT: Move to experiments chapter
% In theory chapter:
The theoretical framework is validated in Section~\ref{sec:exp_validation}.

% In experiments chapter:
\section{Validation of Heliomorphic Completeness}
\label{sec:exp_validation}
We validate Theorem~\ref{thm:heliomorphic_completeness} empirically
by implementing...
```

### When to Move Experiments → Theory:

**Indicators:**
- Proves mathematical properties
- Establishes bounds without data
- Pure mathematical derivation
- No computation required

**Example Migration:**
```latex
% WRONG: In experiments chapter  
\section{Proof of O(n log n) Complexity}
\begin{proof}
By analyzing the algorithm structure...
\end{proof}

% RIGHT: Move to theory chapter
% In theory chapter:
\begin{theorem}[Computational Complexity]
The Elder algorithm has O(n log n) complexity.
\end{theorem}
\begin{proof}
[Mathematical proof]
\end{proof}

% In experiments chapter:
The O(n log n) complexity proven in Theorem~\ref{thm:complexity}
is confirmed by our benchmarks (Figure~\ref{fig:timing}).
```

